I want to say a little bit about cheating prevention. We are going to have real jobs soon that are going to be sent in by a validator of some other subnet and they'll know if a sn12 miner cheats SO if you cheat for example on a job that BittensorGuruPodcast validator of sn17 gave you to evaluate by asking BittensorGuruPodcast sn12 validator to get a 3d asset quality evaluation job done, the sn17 validator will then complain to sn12 validator and send him a cryptographically signed report showing that without a doubt you are a cheater. sn12 validator will not like you anymore, you'll get zero weights from BittensorGuruPodcast until your uid deregistration and it seems bad, but this is far from the worst of what might happen to a cheating sn12 miner.
See, Keith, who is the operator of that validator, has a good reputation and our facilitator will distribute that report to all validators, who will then have an option to trust the other validators.
Therefore if you cheat a small validator that other validators trust, even just one time, you might be punished not just by that one small vali but by more valis

And this is not the worst part yet, because if the job itself is signed by a trusted authority as being deterministic (and I will take upon myself to sign the sn17 3d asset quality evaluator + we might assume that sn12 validators will trust my judgment on sn12 validation, ha ha), then validators who _do not_ trust some validator will be able to run the same job on a trusted compute to determine whether a miner that has been reported as cheating has indeed cheated or not

Funnily enough the signature of the job will be added dynamically, so at the start of the job you won't be able to tell whether that job is going to be at some point signed by a trusted authority or not.

Therefore in order to cheat on sn12 you'll have to be careful to:
- not cheat on the synthetic tasks
- not cheat on non-determinkstic validations of other subnets when they are run by big validators because these will be spot-checked by that subnet validator and it's only a matter of time before you are discovered
- not on small ones either if that small validator is being trusted by enough other valis
- not on deterministic validation jobs because the other valis will just run the thing locally bypassing the trust system even if it's a tiny 1kTAO validator
- not cheat on random organic jobs that might then turn out later to be signed by the subnet owner as deterministic because then the trust system will shred your weights again

And you need to somehow make it so that you'll earn more during that cheating before you get discovered, than you'll spend on the registration fee.
Good luck with that 😂

the dancing algorithm gives a 5% bonus to scores (which after normalizing across all miners to 1 become weights) to miners who significantly change their horde sizes between subsequent synthetic job rounds (this is established on a per validator basis). After each synthetic job test, the number of executors sucessfully finishing it is compared to the analogous number from previous iteration. The bonus is awarded if the high/low ratio is 1.4 or higher. In order to avoid honest validator vtrust drop we suggest that miners change their horde sizes between the 2h windows (in UTC). So for example if between 00:00 02:00 you have 14 executors, between 02:00 and 04:00 you have 10, between 04:00 and 06:00 you have 14 etc. you get the bonus. It does not matter whether you start 00:00 with a high or low number.
